<doc id="246722" wikidata="Q980557" url="?curid=246722" title="Operator norm">
<text>In mathematics, the operator norm measures the &quot;size&quot; of certain linear operators by assigning each a real number called its . Formally, it is a norm defined on the space of bounded linear operators between two given normed vector spaces. Informally, the operator norm formula_1 of a linear map formula_2 is the maximum factor by which it &quot;lengthens&quot; vectors.

== Introduction and definition ==

Given two normed vector spaces formula_3 and formula_4 (over the same base field, either the real numbers formula_5 or the complex numbers formula_6), a linear map formula_7 is continuous if and only if there exists a real number formula_8 such that
formula_9

The norm on the left is the one in formula_4 and the norm on the right is the one in formula_3. 
Intuitively, the continuous operator formula_12 never increases the length of any vector by more than a factor of formula_13 Thus the image of a bounded set under a continuous operator is also bounded. Because of this property, the continuous linear operators are also known as bounded operators. 
In order to &quot;measure the size&quot; of formula_14 one can take the infimum of the numbers formula_8 such that the above inequality holds for all formula_16 
This number represents the maximum scalar factor by which formula_12 &quot;lengthens&quot; vectors. 
In other words, the &quot;size&quot; of formula_12 is measured by how much it &quot;lengthens&quot; vectors in the &quot;biggest&quot; case. So we define the operator norm of formula_12 as
formula_20

The infimum is attained as the set of all such formula_8 is closed, nonempty, and bounded from below.

It is important to bear in mind that this operator norm depends on the choice of norms for the normed vector spaces formula_3 and formula_4.

== Examples ==

Every real formula_24-by-formula_25 matrix corresponds to a linear map from formula_26 to formula_27 Each pair of the plethora of (vector) norms applicable to real vector spaces induces an operator norm for all formula_24-by-formula_25 matrices of real numbers; these induced norms form a subset of matrix norms.

If we specifically choose the Euclidean norm on both formula_26 and formula_31 then the matrix norm given to a matrix formula_12 is the square root of the largest eigenvalue of the matrix formula_33 (where formula_34 denotes the conjugate transpose of formula_12). 
This is equivalent to assigning the largest singular value of formula_36

Passing to a typical infinite-dimensional example, consider the sequence space formula_37 which is an L&quot;p&quot; space, defined by
formula_38

This can be viewed as an infinite-dimensional analogue of the Euclidean space formula_39 
Now consider a bounded sequence formula_40 The sequence formula_41 is an element of the space formula_42 with a norm given by
formula_43

Define an operator formula_44 by pointwise multiplication:
formula_45

The operator formula_44 is bounded with operator norm
formula_47

This discussion extends directly to the case where formula_48 is replaced by a general formula_49 space with formula_50 and formula_51 replaced by formula_52

==Equivalent definitions==

Let formula_7 be a linear operator between normed spaces. The first four definitions are always equivalent, and if in addition formula_54 then they are all equivalent:
:formula_55
If formula_56 then the sets in the last two rows will be empty, and consequently their supremums over the set formula_57 will equal formula_58 instead of the correct value of formula_59 If the supremum is taken over the set formula_60 instead, then the supremum of the empty set is formula_61 and the formulas hold for any formula_62 

Importantly, a linear operator formula_7 is not, in general, guaranteed to achieve its norm formula_64 on the closed unit ball formula_65 meaning that there might not exist any vector formula_66 of norm formula_67 such that formula_68 (if such a vector does exist and if formula_69 then formula_70 would necessarily have unit norm formula_71). R.C. James proved James&#x27;s theorem in 1964, which states that a Banach space formula_3 is reflexive if and only if every bounded linear functional formula_73 achieves its norm on the closed unit ball. 
It follows, in particular, that every non-reflexive Banach space has some bounded linear functional (a type of bounded linear operator) that does not achieve its norm on the closed unit ball.

If formula_7 is bounded then 
