where formula_77 is the transpose of formula_78 which is the linear operator defined by formula_79

== Properties ==

The operator norm is indeed a norm on the space of all bounded operators between formula_3 and formula_4. This means
formula_82
formula_83
formula_84

The following inequality is an immediate consequence of the definition:
formula_85

The operator norm is also compatible with the composition, or multiplication, of operators: if formula_3, formula_4 and formula_88 are three normed spaces over the same base field, and formula_7 and formula_90 are two bounded operators, then it is a sub-multiplicative norm, that is: 
formula_91

For bounded operators on formula_3, this implies that operator multiplication is jointly continuous.

It follows from the definition that if a sequence of operators converges in operator norm, it converges uniformly on bounded sets.

== Table of common operator norms ==

By choosing different norms for the codomain, used in computing formula_93, and the domain, used in computing formula_94, we obtain different values for the operator norm. Some common operator norms are easy to calculate, and others are NP-hard. 
Except for the NP-hard norms, all these norms can be calculated in formula_95 operations (for an formula_96 matrix), with the exception of the formula_97 norm (which requires formula_98 operations for the exact answer, or fewer if you approximate it with the power method or Lanczos iterations).

The norm of the adjoint or transpose can be computed as follows. 
