== Operators on a Hilbert space ==

Suppose formula_105 is a real or complex Hilbert space. If formula_106 is a bounded linear operator, then we have
formula_107
and
formula_108
where formula_34 denotes the adjoint operator of formula_12 (which in Euclidean spaces with the standard inner product corresponds to the conjugate transpose of the matrix formula_12).

In general, the spectral radius of formula_12 is bounded above by the operator norm of formula_12:
formula_114

To see why equality may not always hold, consider the Jordan canonical form of a matrix in the finite-dimensional case. Because there are non-zero entries on the superdiagonal, equality may be violated. The quasinilpotent operators is one class of such examples. A nonzero quasinilpotent operator formula_12 has spectrum formula_116 So formula_117 while formula_118

However, when a matrix formula_119 is normal, its Jordan canonical form is diagonal (up to unitary equivalence); this is the spectral theorem. In that case it is easy to see that
formula_120

This formula can sometimes be used to compute the operator norm of a given bounded operator formula_12: define the Hermitian operator formula_122 determine its spectral radius, and take the square root to obtain the operator norm of formula_36

The space of bounded operators on formula_124 with the topology induced by operator norm, is not separable. 
For example, consider the Lp space formula_125 which is a Hilbert space. 
For formula_126 let formula_127 be the characteristic function of formula_128 and formula_129 be the multiplication operator given by formula_130 that is,
formula_131

Then each formula_129 is a bounded operator with operator norm 1 and
formula_133

But formula_134 is an uncountable set. 
This implies the space of bounded operators on formula_135 is not separable, in operator norm. 
One can compare this with the fact that the sequence space formula_136 is not separable.

The associative algebra of all bounded operators on a Hilbert space, together with the operator norm and the adjoint operation, yields a C*-algebra.

