Another useful application of virtual bundles is with the definition of a virtual tangent bundle of an intersection of spaces: Let formula_154 be projective subvarieties of a smooth projective variety. Then, we can define the virtual tangent bundle of their intersection formula_155 as

:formula_156

Kontsevich uses this construction in one of his papers.

===Chern characters===

Chern classes can be used to construct a homomorphism of rings from the topological K-theory of a space to (the completion of) its rational cohomology. For a line bundle &quot;L&quot;, the Chern character ch is defined by

:formula_157

More generally, if formula_158 is a direct sum of line bundles, with first Chern classes formula_159 the Chern character is defined additively

:formula_160

The Chern character is useful in part because it facilitates the computation of the Chern class of a tensor product. The Chern character is used in the Hirzebruch–Riemann–Roch theorem.

==Equivariant K-theory==
The equivariant algebraic K-theory is an algebraic K-theory associated to the category formula_161 of equivariant coherent sheaves on an algebraic scheme formula_46 with action of a linear algebraic group formula_163, via Quillen&#x27;s Q-construction; thus, by definition,

:formula_164

In particular, formula_165 is the Grothendieck group of formula_161. The theory was developed by R. W. Thomason in 1980s. Specifically, he proved equivariant analogs of fundamental theorems such as the localization theorem.

